<paragraph blockId="5.[994,1251,765,791]" box="[994,1251,765,791]" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Greater horseshoe bat</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="76" pageId="5" pageNumber="75" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[816,1429,832,1329]" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">
<collectionCode box="[854,888,832,858]" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">FA</collectionCode>
— 56.5–62.0 mm, mass — 
<quantity box="[1273,1425,832,858]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="2.455" metricValueMax="3.26" metricValueMin="1.65" pageId="5" pageNumber="75" unit="g" value="24.55" valueMax="32.6" valueMin="16.5">16.5–32.6 g</quantity>
. A widespread bat in 
<collectingCountry box="[1058,1133,866,892]" name="China" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">China</collectingCountry>
: we captured bats in 
<collectingRegion country="China" name="Beijing" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Beijing</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[881,985,899,925]" country="China" name="Guangxi" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Guangxi</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1001,1081,899,925]" country="China" name="Henan" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Henan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1096,1171,899,925]" country="China" name="Hubei" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Hubei</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1187,1275,899,925]" country="China" name="Jiangxi" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Jiangxi</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1291,1344,899,925]" country="China" name="Jilin" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Jilin</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion country="China" name="Shandong" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Shandong</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[889,973,933,959]" country="China" name="Shanxi" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Shanxi</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[985,1082,933,959]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Sichuan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1093,1177,933,959]" name="China" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Tianjin</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1232,1326,933,959]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
. Bats assigned to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schreber" baseAuthorityYear="1774" box="[942,1161,967,993]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="75" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ferrumequinum">
<emphasis box="[942,1161,967,993]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">R. ferrumequinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[1210,1280,967,993]" name="China" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">China</collectingCountry>
have lower call frequencies and longer forearms (72.0–83.5 kHz, 56.5–62.0 mm, respectively) than those sampled in continental Europe and the 
<collectingCountry box="[1214,1256,1068,1094]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">UK</collectingCountry>
(81–84 kHz, 50.6–59.0 mm 
<collectionCode box="[999,1033,1101,1127]" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">FA</collectionCode>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[1075,1117,1101,1127]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">UK</collectingCountry>
— 
<bibRefCitation author="HELLER, K. - G. &amp; O. V. HELVERSEN" pageId="5" pageNumber="75" pagination="178 - 186" refId="ref11405" refString="HELLER, K. - G., and O. V. HELVERSEN. 1989. Resource partitioning of sonar frequency bands in rhinolophoid bats. Oecologia, 80: 178 - 186." type="journal article" year="1989">Heller and Helversen, 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="JONES, G. &amp; J. M. V. RAYNER" box="[896,1194,1135,1161]" pageId="5" pageNumber="75" pagination="183 - 191" refId="ref11588" refString="JONES, G., and J. M. V. RAYNER. 1990. Foraging behavior and echolocation of wild horseshoe bats Rhinolophus ferrumequinum and R. hipposideros (Chiroptera, Rhinolophidae). Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology, 25: 183 - 191." type="journal article" year="1990">Jones and Rayner, 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="PARK, K. J. &amp; G. JONES &amp; R. D. RANSOME" box="[1212,1424,1135,1161]" pageId="5" pageNumber="75" pagination="580 - 588" refId="ref11989" refString="PARK, K. J., G. JONES, and R. D. RANSOME. 2000. Torpor, arousal and activity of hibernating greater horseshoe bats (Rhinolophus ferrumequinum). Functional Ecology, 14: 580 - 588." type="journal article" year="2000">
Park 
<emphasis box="[1278,1335,1135,1161]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">et al</emphasis>
., 2000
</bibRefCitation>
; Andrews and Andrews, 2003; 
<bibRefCitation author="RANSOME, R. D." box="[1222,1417,1168,1194]" pageId="5" pageNumber="75" refId="ref12082" refString="RANSOME, R. D. 2008. Greater horseshoe bat. Pp. 298 - 306, in Mammals of the British Isles: handbook, 4 th edition (S. HARRIS and D. W. YALDEN, eds.). The Mammal Society, Southampton, 800 pp." type="book" year="2008">Ransome 2008</bibRefCitation>
). Genetic analyses of microsatellite loci and mitochondrial DNA reveal deep divisions among populations within 
<collectingCountry box="[988,1061,1269,1295]" name="China" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">China</collectingCountry>
, and also between the Chinese populations and those from the Middle East and
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3944521" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3944521" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3944521/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="75" startId="5.[159,172,1969,1990]" targetBox="[395,1199,1424,1937]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[159,1429,1969,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">
FIG. 3. Relationship between frequency of echolocation calls from handheld bats (resting frequency) and forearm length for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="K. Andersen" authorityYear="1905" box="[590,785,1997,2018]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="75" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sinicus">
<emphasis box="[590,785,1997,2018]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">Rhinolophus sinicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(D) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Horsfield" authorityYear="1823" box="[871,959,1997,2018]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="75" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis box="[871,959,1997,2018]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="75">R. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(-)
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[159,772,223,1063]" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">
Europe (
<bibRefCitation author="ROSSITER, S. J. &amp; P. BENDA &amp; C. DIETZ &amp; S. ZHANG &amp; G. JONES" box="[260,504,223,249]" pageId="6" pageNumber="76" pagination="4699 - 4714" refId="ref12175" refString="ROSSITER, S. J., P. BENDA, C. DIETZ, S. ZHANG, and G. JONES. 2007. Rangewide phylogeography in the greater horseshoe bat inferred from microsatellites: implications for population history, taxonomy, and conservation. Molecular Ecology, 16: 4699 - 4714." type="journal article" year="2007">
Rossiter 
<emphasis box="[366,419,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">et al</emphasis>
., 2007
</bibRefCitation>
; Flanders 
<emphasis box="[627,687,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">et al.</emphasis>
2009). Bats from southwest 
<collectingCountry box="[415,485,257,283]" name="China" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">China</collectingCountry>
typically emitted echolocation calls with 
<collectionCode box="[381,484,291,317]" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">FMAXE</collectionCode>
at 72.0 kHz to 73.9 kHz (
<collectingRegion box="[166,258,325,351]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[334,431,325,351]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">Sichuan</collectingRegion>
, respectively), while those from east 
<collectingCountry box="[287,357,359,385]" name="China" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">China</collectingCountry>
are higher again (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[593,641,358,384]" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">♂♂</emphasis>
74.8–76.8 kHz; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[232,280,392,418]" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">♀♀</emphasis>
76.4–77.1 kHz). Moreover, bats from 
<collectingCountry box="[159,226,426,452]" name="Japan" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">Japan</collectingCountry>
that are usually considered a discrete subspecies (
<emphasis box="[260,397,460,486]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">R. f. nippon</emphasis>
) show a further decrease in call frequency (ca. 65 kHz — 
<bibRefCitation author="TANIGUCHI, I." box="[466,661,494,520]" pageId="6" pageNumber="76" pagination="185 - 188" refId="ref12546" refString="TANIGUCHI, I. 1985. Echolocation sounds and hearing of the greater Japanese horseshoe bat (Rhinolophus ferrumequinum nippon). Journal of Comparative Physiology, 156 A: 185 - 188." type="journal article" year="1985">Taniguchi, 1985</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="FUKUI, D. &amp; N. AGETSUMA &amp; D. A. HILL" pageId="6" pageNumber="76" pagination="947 - 955" refId="ref11291" refString="FUKUI, D., N. AGETSUMA, and D. A. HILL. 2004. Acoustic identification of eight species of bat (Mammalia: Chiroptera) inhabiting forests of southern Hokkaido, Japan: potential for conservation monitoring. Zoological Science, 21: 947 - 955." type="journal article" year="2004">
<collectingRegion box="[673,741,494,520]" country="Japan" name="Fukui" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">Fukui</collectingRegion>
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">et al.</emphasis>
, 2004
</bibRefCitation>
) and are typically larger than most bats on the Chinese mainland. In conflict with this general trend was one bat from Jilin that emitted echolocation calls at 65 kHz and also appeared to show greater mtDNA sequence affiliation to the bats from 
<collectingCountry box="[159,230,698,724]" name="Japan" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">Japan</collectingCountry>
. Hence it is likely that the 
<emphasis box="[549,630,698,724]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">nippon</emphasis>
lineage has recolonised 
<collectingCountry box="[299,368,732,758]" name="China" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">China</collectingCountry>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[437,503,732,758]" name="Japan" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">Japan</collectingCountry>
(Flanders 
<emphasis box="[625,676,732,758]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">et al</emphasis>
., 2009). Such large differences in call frequency and corresponding genetic distinctiveness suggest that populations of this species in 
<collectingCountry box="[456,526,833,859]" name="China" pageId="6" pageNumber="76">China</collectingCountry>
might warrant taxonomic revision.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
